1. Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

1.1 Objective¶

  • Identify and classify the sentiment of twitter post about airlines services

1.2 Data Dictionary¶

  • tweet_id
  • airline_sentiment
  • airline_sentiment_confidence
  • negativereason
  • negativereason_confidence
  • airline
  • airline_sentiment_gold
  • name
  • negativereason_gold
  • retweet_count
  • text
  • tweet_coord
  • tweet_created
  • tweet_location
  • user_timezone

1.3 Questions to be answered¶

  • What are the main words that identify the positive and negative sentiment for US Airline Tweets?
  • What is the perception about the service of US Airlines?

In [12]:
#function to plot the distribution of the feature
def bar_plot(data, feature):
    plot = sns.countplot(y=feature, data=data, order=data[feature].value_counts().index)
    total = len(data)
    for p in plot.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_width()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        plot.annotate(percentage, (x, y),ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

5.5 Remove Special Characters¶

In [36]:
def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

data_clean['text'] = data_clean.apply(lambda row: remove_non_ascii(row['text']), axis=1)

5.6 Remove Punctuations¶

In [37]:
def remove_punctuation(words):
    """Remove punctuation from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

data_clean['text'] = data_clean.apply(lambda row: remove_punctuation(row['text']), axis=1)

def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

5.8 Remove Stopwords¶

In [39]:
# List of stopwords
stw = stopwords.words('english')

# Set custom stop-word's list as not, couldn't etc. words matter in Sentiment, so not removing them from original data.
customw = ['not', "couldn't", 'didn', "didn't", 'doesn', "doesn't", 'hadn', "hadn't", 'hasn',
        "hasn't", 'haven', "haven't", 'isn', "isn't", 'ma', 'mightn', "mightn't", 'mustn',
        "mustn't", 'needn', "needn't", 'shan', "shan't", 'shouldn', "shouldn't", 'wasn',
        "wasn't", 'weren', "weren't", 'won', "won't", 'wouldn', "wouldn't"]

stw = list(set(stw) - set(customw))    

def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stw:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

data_clean['text'] = data_clean.apply(lambda row: remove_stopwords(row['text']), axis=1)
data_clean.head()

6 Model Building¶

6.1 Functions to evaluate models¶

In [42]:
def metrics_score(model, model_name, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1 score
    model: classifier to predict values of X
    train, test: Independent features
    train_y,test_y: Dependent variable
    '''
    
    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    score_dict = {'Model':model_name,
                  'Accuracy on training set' : accuracy_score(pred_train,y_train),
                  'Accuracy on validation set': accuracy_score(pred_test,y_test),
                  'Recall on training set': recall_score(y_train,pred_train,average='macro'),
                  'Recall on validation set': recall_score(y_test,pred_test,average='macro'),
                  'Precision on training set': precision_score(y_train,pred_train,average='macro'),
                  'Precision on validation set': precision_score(y_test,pred_test,average='macro'),
                  'F1 on training set': f1_score(y_train,pred_train,average='macro'),
                  'F1 on validation set': f1_score(y_test,pred_test,average='macro')
                 }
    # Create a dataframe with scores
    scores = pd.DataFrame(score_dict,index=[0])
    # return the df
    return scores
In [43]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model, X_test, y_test):
    # Test Prediction 
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    # Confusion matrix normalized per category true value
    cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred, normalize='true')
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cf_matrix, 
                         index = ['negative','neutral','positive'],
                         columns = ['negative','neutral','positive'])
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True);

7.1 Split data into train and test¶

In [46]:
# Splitting data into training, validation and test set:
# first we split data into 2 parts, say temporary and test
X_temp, X_test, y_temp, y_test = train_test_split(data_countvec, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1, stratify=y)

9 Model performances on test set¶

Now, we are going to compare all models on test set

In [67]:
# Function to calculate different metric scores of the classification model
def metrics_score_test(model,test,test_y,model_name=''):
    '''
    Inputs:
        model: classifier to predict values of X
        test: Independent features in test sets
        test_y: Dependent variable in test sets
        threshold: thresold for classifiying the observation as 1
        model_name: Name of the model
    '''
    
    # Make the prediction of the model in train and test sets
    pred_test = model.predict(test)

    # Calculate scores and save them in a dictionary
    score_dict = {'Model':model_name,
                  'Accuracy on test set': accuracy_score(pred_test,test_y),
                  'Recall on test set': recall_score(test_y,pred_test,average='macro'),
                  'Precision on test set': precision_score(test_y,pred_test,average='macro'),
                  'F1 on test set': f1_score(test_y,pred_test,average='macro')
                 }
    
    # Create a dataframe with scores
    scores = pd.DataFrame(score_dict,index=[0])
    # return the df
    return scores
In [68]:
# Create dataframe with scores on Test dataset for all models
all_scores = pd.concat(
    [# Count Vectorizer Models
     metrics_score_test(model_rf_count,X_test,y_test,model_name='Random Forest Count Vectorizer'),
     metrics_score_test(model_xgb_count,X_test,y_test,model_name='XGBoost Count Vectorizer'),
     metrics_score_test(xgb_estimator,X_test,y_test,model_name='Tuned XGBoost Count Vectorizer'),
     # Tf-IDF Vectorizer Models
     metrics_score_test(model_rf_tfidf,X_test2,y_test2,model_name='Random Forest Tf-IDF Vectorizer'),
     metrics_score_test(model_xgb_tfidf,X_test2,y_test2,model_name='XGBoost Tf-IDF Vectorizer'),
     metrics_score_test(xgb_estimator_tf,X_test2,y_test2,model_name='Tuned XGBoost Tf-IDF Vectorizer'),
     
    ],
    axis=0,
    ignore_index=True)
all_scores.sort_values(by=['Accuracy on test set'], ascending=False)

11 Conclusions¶

  • In this project we were able to create a classification model to determine the sentiment of twitter post related to the service of US Airlines
  • In order to create an useful data set and model we performed several steps:
    • Data pre-processing: Cleaning the text removing non-text characters and symbols and lemmatize text
    • Convert bag of words on numerical data using CountVectorizer and Tf-IDF vectorizer
    • Fit classifier model. In our project we use Random Forest and XGBoost, but any other classifier model could be used.
  • Our models have relatively good accuracy of 78%. We reach this level after we tuned the XGBoost models in order to reduce the overfitting
  • Both CountVectorizer and Tf-IDF Vectorizer presents similar results for this specific data set.
